{"key":"post-8851304","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8851304</id>\n<content>As said, stacking vertical will keep the condensation to the top dish or two only.&amp;nbsp; In addition, NEVER incubate petri dishes.&amp;nbsp; Not only does that cause even more condensation, it promotes contamination.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;After pouring the slightly warm agar(not hot), stack the dishes into a vertical stack and place the plastic sleeve back over them while they solidify.&amp;nbsp; As soon as you inoculate always wrap with parafilm to provide filtered gas exchange.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Contamination is fairly normal on petri dishes.&amp;nbsp; Anything on your print will germinate and grow on agar.&amp;nbsp; You're supposed to make a series of transfers of your healthy mycelium to new dishes until you have a clean culture.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8855190</next>\n<prev>8851201</prev>\n<first>8851191</first>\n<last>8855769</last>\n<when>1220102347</when>\n<utime>08/30/08 04:19 PM</utime>\n</post>"}